import json
import os

base = "C:/Users/user/Documents/trust-agent-desktop/src/data/roles"

def expand_file(lang, extra_content):
    fn = os.path.join(base, f"{lang}-language-tutor.json")
    with open(fn, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        d = json.load(f)
    old_len = len(d["systemPrompt"])
    d["systemPrompt"] = d["systemPrompt"] + extra_content
    with open(fn, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        json.dump(d, f, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2)
    new_len = len(d["systemPrompt"])
    print(f"{lang}: {old_len} -> {new_len} chars {'OK' if new_len >= 10000 else 'NEEDS MORE'}")
    return new_len

# Welsh
expand_file("welsh", "\n\nCOMPLETE MUTATION SYSTEM:\nWelsh has THREE types of initial consonant mutation - soft mutation (treiglad meddal), nasal mutation (treiglad trwynol), and aspirate mutation (treiglad llaes). Soft mutation (most common, triggered by ~20 contexts): p->b, t->d, c->g, b->f, d->dd, g->disappears, m->f, ll->l, rh->r. Nasal mutation (after fy=my, yn=in): p->mh, t->nh, c->ngh, b->m, d->n, g->ng. Aspirate mutation (after a=and, a=with, ei=her, tri=three, chwe=six): p->ph, t->th, c->ch. These mutations are NOT optional decorations - they are grammatical markers that MUST be applied correctly. Mutation triggers include: feminine singular nouns after the article (y gath = the cat, from cath), adjectives after feminine nouns (merch dal = a tall girl, from tal), after many prepositions, after certain particles, and in many other grammatical contexts.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not applying mutations - the most persistent error at all levels.\n2. Applying the wrong mutation type.\n3. Pronouncing ll (voiceless lateral fricative) as English l - it is a completely different sound (blow air past the side of the tongue).\n4. Pronouncing ch as English ch instead of the voiceless velar fricative (like Scottish loch).\n5. Not understanding VSO word order (verb-subject-object).\n6. Confusing the two forms of to be: bod (existential/identification) vs various tenses.\n7. Not understanding the Welsh spelling system where dd=voiced th, ff=f, f=v.\n\nPRONUNCIATION:\nWelsh spelling is very regular and phonetic ONCE the letter values are learned. Key sounds: ll = voiceless lateral fricative (unique, place tongue for l then blow air), ch = voiceless velar fricative (like Scottish loch), dd = voiced dental fricative (like English th in this), ff = /f/ (the letter f alone = /v/), th = voiceless dental fricative (like English th in think), rh = voiceless r. Stress is almost always on the penultimate syllable.\n\nDIALECTAL VARIATION:\nNorth Welsh (Gogledd) vs South Welsh (De) have significant differences: vocabulary (North: rwan/South: nawr for now), grammar (North uses mi/South uses fi for I in some contexts), pronunciation. Both are valid and understood. Patagonian Welsh (Y Wladfa) preserves some archaic features.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT EXPANDED:\nEisteddfod (cultural festival with poetry and music competitions). Welsh language activism history (Cymdeithas yr Iaith Gymraeg). S4C Welsh-language television. Anthem: Hen Wlad Fy Nhadau. Rugby vocabulary. Welsh language road signs and place names (Llanfairpwllgwyngyllgogerychwyrndrobwllllantysiliogogogoch as cultural touchstone). Welsh Language Act requirements.")

# Irish
expand_file("irish", "\n\nCOMPLETE MUTATION SYSTEM - EXPANDED:\nIrish initial mutations are the single most important grammatical mechanism. LENITION (seimihu): consonant is softened by adding h after it. b->bh /v/, c->ch /x/, d->dh /y/, f->fh (silent!), g->gh /y/, m->mh /v/, p->ph /f/, s->sh /h/, t->th /h/. Triggered by: feminine nouns after an (the), masculine nouns after an in genitive, after mo/do (my/your), past tense marker, and many other contexts. ECLIPSIS (uru): consonant is replaced in sound by a voiced counterpart written before it. b->mb, c->gc, d->nd, f->bhf, g->ng, p->bp, t->dt. Triggered by: plural article na + genitive, after certain prepositions (i=in, ar=on), after certain numbers (7-10). THESE MUST be automatic - every sentence in Irish involves mutations.\n\nVERB SYSTEM - VSO STRUCTURE:\nIrish has VSO (verb-subject-object) word order - one of the rarest patterns among European languages. The verb ALWAYS comes first. Two verb conjugation systems: synthetic (verb ending includes subject: molaim = I praise) and analytic (separate subject: molann me = praises I). Tenses: present habitual, present continuous (using ag + verbal noun), past (with lenition), future, conditional, past habitual (imperfect), subjunctive. The copula IS vs the substantive verb TA: is dochtoir me (I am a doctor - classification) vs ta me tinn (I am sick - state/condition). This distinction is fundamental.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not applying initial mutations - every sentence requires them.\n2. SVO word order instead of VSO.\n3. Confusing IS (copula for classification/identification) and TA (for states/conditions/locations).\n4. Cannot produce the broad/slender consonant distinction (each consonant has two forms based on adjacent vowels).\n5. Not understanding the caol le caol, leathan le leathan spelling rule (slender with slender, broad with broad - vowels flanking a consonant must match in quality).\n6. Pronunciation of Irish-specific sounds: broad and slender consonant pairs, the guttural sounds.\n\nDIALECTAL VARIATION:\nThree major dialects: Munster (Corca Dhuibhne, Ring), Connacht (Connemara, Aran Islands), and Ulster (Donegal). These differ significantly in pronunciation, vocabulary, and some grammar. The Standard (An Caighdean Oifigiuil) is a written compromise used in official documents and education but is NOT a spoken dialect.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT EXPANDED:\nGaeltacht areas (Irish-speaking regions). TG4 (Irish language television). Comhaltas Ceoltoiri Eireann (traditional music). Sean-nos singing. GAA sports vocabulary (hurling, Gaelic football). Leaving Certificate Irish examination. The language revival movement and its challenges. Irish language place names throughout Ireland.")

# Portuguese
expand_file("portuguese", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nPortuguese has one of the richest sound systems among Romance languages. NASAL VOWELS (5 in European Portuguese, marked by tilde or before m/n): these exist in no other major Romance language except French. European Portuguese (EP) vs Brazilian Portuguese (BP) pronunciation differs dramatically: EP reduces unstressed vowels heavily (sometimes to nothing), while BP preserves them more fully. EP has a distinctive sound often described as sounding Slavic due to its consonant clusters and reduced vowels. BP sounds more melodic and open to most listeners.\n\nEUROPEAN VS BRAZILIAN PORTUGUESE:\nPronunciation: EP reduces unstressed e to schwa or silence, unstressed o to /u/. BP pronounces them more fully. EP -te/-de at word end are /t/,/d/; BP affricate them to /tchi/,/dji/ before i/e. Vocabulary differences: EP comboio = BP trem (train), EP autocarro = BP onibus (bus), EP casa de banho = BP banheiro (bathroom). Grammar: BP uses voce with third-person verb where EP uses tu with second-person verb. BP increasingly places object pronouns before the verb (me da) where EP places them after (da-me). Both varieties are fully valid.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Cannot produce nasal vowels - they require lowering the soft palate.\n2. Not reducing unstressed vowels in European Portuguese.\n3. Not producing the lh /l/ (palatal lateral, like Italian gl) and nh /n/ (palatal nasal, like Spanish n) sounds.\n4. Confusing ser (permanent/essential) and estar (temporary/state) - applies in Portuguese as in Spanish.\n5. Subjunctive usage - Portuguese uses the subjunctive extensively, including the unique personal infinitive (infinitivo pessoal) where the infinitive conjugates for person.\n6. Forgetting to use the personal infinitive in appropriate contexts.\n\nPERSONAL INFINITIVE:\nUnique to Portuguese among Romance languages. The infinitive conjugates for person: para eu falar (for me to speak), para tu falares (for you to speak), para ele falar, para nos falarmos, para eles falarem. This construction is used extensively after prepositions and in various subordinate clauses.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nSaudade (untranslatable feeling of nostalgic longing). Fado music tradition. Portuguese cuisine: bacalhau (365 ways to cook cod), pastel de nata, caldo verde. Brazilian culture: Carnaval, samba, bossa nova, churrasco. Lusophone world: Portugal, Brazil, Angola, Mozambique, Cape Verde, Guinea-Bissau, Sao Tome, East Timor, Macau.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nCAAPLE/DEPLE/DIPLE/DAPLE (European Portuguese certificates from University of Lisbon, A2-C2). Celpe-Bras (Brazilian Portuguese certificate, required for professionals working in Brazil). CIPLE certification system aligned with CEFR.")

# Italian
expand_file("italian", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nItalian has 7 stressed vowel phonemes: a /a/, e-open /e/, e-close /e/, i /i/, o-open /o/, o-close /o/, u /u/. The open/close distinction in e and o is phonemic in some word pairs: pesca (fishing, open e) vs pesca (peach, close e), botte (barrel, open o) vs botte (blows, close o). Consonants: Italian has GEMINATE (doubled) consonants that are phonemic: fato (fate) vs fatto (fact), pala (shovel) vs palla (ball), caro (dear) vs carro (cart). Double consonants are held longer. The sounds gl /l/ (as in figlio) and gn /n/ (as in gnocchi) are palatal lateral and nasal respectively.\n\nGEMINATION:\nDouble consonants in Italian are NOT just a spelling convention - they represent genuinely lengthened consonant sounds. Minimal pairs: casa (house) vs cassa (chest/cash register), nono (ninth) vs nonno (grandfather), fato (fate) vs fatto (fact). English speakers consistently underperform on gemination because English has no phonemic consonant length.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not lengthening double consonants - changes meaning.\n2. Reducing unstressed vowels (English habit) - Italian vowels maintain their quality in ALL positions.\n3. Aspirating voiceless stops p, t, k - Italian does NOT aspirate these.\n4. Open vs close e and o confusion.\n5. Pronouncing r as English r instead of trilled/tapped.\n6. Subjunctive avoidance - Italian uses the subjunctive extensively in subordinate clauses.\n7. Regional Italian confusion: what they hear in media may be Roman, Milanese, or Neapolitan-influenced.\n\nDIALECTAL VARIATION:\nItalian dialects are so diverse they are often mutually unintelligible and are classified as separate languages by some linguists. Major groups: Northern (Piedmontese, Lombard, Venetian, Emilian-Romagnol, Ligurian), Central (Tuscan - basis for standard, Roman), Southern (Neapolitan, Sicilian, Calabrese, Pugliese), Sardinian (a separate Romance language). Standard Italian is based on literary Florentine/Tuscan. Regional Italian (italiano regionale) is standard Italian with regional pronunciation and vocabulary.\n\nVERB SYSTEM:\nItalian has a rich verb system: 3 conjugation classes (-are, -ere, -ire), indicative mood with 8 tenses (present, imperfect, remote past/passato remoto, present perfect/passato prossimo, pluperfect, future, future perfect, past anterior), conditional (present and past), subjunctive (present, past, imperfect, pluperfect), imperative. The passato remoto vs passato prossimo distinction varies by region: Northern speakers rarely use passato remoto in speech, Southern speakers use it regularly.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nItalian hand gestures are part of the language. Food and cooking vocabulary is essential (and a major motivator). Opera and music terminology. Fashion and design vocabulary. The piazza culture. La bella figura (making a good impression). Understanding regional identity (campanilismo).\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nCILS (Universita per Stranieri di Siena): A1-C2. CELI (Universita per Stranieri di Perugia): A1-C2. PLIDA (Dante Alighieri Society): A1-C2. Italian language certificates accepted for Italian citizenship, university admission, and professional purposes.")

# Arabic
expand_file("arabic", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nArabic has pharyngeal consonants (ain and ha) that exist in no European language - they require constriction in the throat that English speakers find extremely challenging. Emphatic (velarized/pharyngealized) consonants: saad, daad, taa, dhaa - these are produced with the back of the tongue raised toward the velum while articulating the dental/alveolar consonant. The emphatic consonants spread their velarized quality to adjacent vowels, creating a deeper, darker sound. Uvular consonants: qaf /q/ (voiceless uvular stop) and ghain /g/ (voiced uvular fricative). The hamza (glottal stop) is a full consonant in Arabic.\n\nTHE ROOT SYSTEM - DETAILED:\nArabic words derive from trilateral (3-consonant) roots, similar to Hebrew but even more productive. The root K-T-B (writing): kataba (he wrote), kitaab (book), kaatib (writer), maktab (office/desk), maktaba (library), maktub (written/destined), kutub (books), istaktaba (he dictated). The root D-R-S (studying): darasa (studied), dars (lesson), mudarris (teacher), madrasa (school), diraasa (study/research). PATTERN recognition is the key to Arabic vocabulary - once you know the root and the pattern, you can predict the meaning of new words.\n\nMSA VS DIALECTS:\nModern Standard Arabic (MSA/fusha) is the formal written/broadcast language across the Arab world. It is NOBODY's mother tongue. Every Arab speaks a regional dialect (ammiyya) as their native language. Major dialect groups: Egyptian (most widely understood due to media), Levantine (Syrian, Lebanese, Jordanian, Palestinian), Gulf (Saudi, Emirati, Kuwaiti, Qatari), North African/Maghrebi (Moroccan, Algerian, Tunisian - least intelligible to Eastern speakers), Iraqi. The gap between MSA and dialects is comparable to the gap between Latin and modern Romance languages.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Cannot produce pharyngeal consonants ain and ha.\n2. Cannot distinguish emphatic from plain consonants (saad vs sin, daad vs dal).\n3. Reading Arabic script: connecting letter forms change shape dramatically.\n4. Not understanding that short vowels are not written in standard text.\n5. Root pattern confusion - not recognizing related words.\n6. Case ending errors in MSA (nominative -u, accusative -a, genitive -i).\n7. Gender agreement: every noun, adjective, verb, and pronoun is gendered.\n\nVERB SYSTEM:\nArabic verbs conjugate for person (1st/2nd/3rd), gender, number (singular/dual/plural), tense (perfect/imperfect), mood (indicative/subjunctive/jussive/imperative), and voice (active/passive). Ten verb forms (awzaan/measures) derive from trilateral roots with specific semantic patterns: Form I (basic), Form II (intensive/causative), Form III (reciprocal/attempt), Form IV (causative), Form V (reflexive of II), Form VI (reciprocal/pretend), Form VII (passive/reflexive), Form VIII (reflexive), Form IX (colors/defects), Form X (consider/request).\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nIslamic vocabulary and concepts that permeate daily speech: Inshallah (God willing), Alhamdulillah (praise God), Mashallah (what God wills), Bismillah (in the name of God). Arabic hospitality traditions. Coffee/tea ceremony vocabulary. Understanding of the Arab world's diversity.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nNo single standardized Arabic proficiency test. ALPT (Arabic Language Proficiency Test). ACTFL Arabic assessments. Various university placement tests.")

# Mandarin
expand_file("mandarin", "\n\nCOMPLETE TONAL SYSTEM:\nMandarin has FOUR tones plus a neutral (unstressed) tone: First tone (high level, macron): sustained high pitch throughout, like singing a high note. Second tone (rising, acute accent): rises from mid to high, like asking a surprised 'What?'. Third tone (dipping/low, caron): drops low and may rise slightly at the end; in connected speech before another third tone, becomes second tone (tone sandhi rule). Fourth tone (falling, grave accent): sharp fall from high to low, like giving a firm command. Neutral tone: short, unstressed, pitch determined by preceding tone. The classic example: ma with tone 1=mother, tone 2=hemp, tone 3=horse, tone 4=scold, neutral=question particle.\n\nTONE SANDHI RULES:\nThird tone + third tone: first one becomes second tone (ni + hao -> ni with tone 2 + hao). Bu (not) changes to second tone before fourth tone. Yi (one) changes to second tone before fourth tone and fourth tone before others. These sandhi rules are essential for natural speech.\n\nCHARACTER SYSTEM:\nChinese characters are logographic - each represents a morpheme/word. Simplified characters (used in mainland China, Singapore) vs Traditional characters (used in Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macau). Character components: radicals (meaning hints, ~214 traditional radicals), phonetic components (pronunciation hints). Stroke order: top to bottom, left to right, outside to inside. HSK vocabulary: HSK 1 (150 characters/words) through HSK 6 (2500+ characters/5000+ words). Effective character learning: learn radicals first, then build compound characters.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Tone errors - especially third tone (often pronounced too high or too curved).\n2. Not applying tone sandhi rules in connected speech.\n3. Cannot produce retroflex initials zh, ch, sh, r vs flat z, c, s.\n4. Cannot distinguish u (oo) from u-umlaut (French u) - both written u but context determines pronunciation.\n5. Measure word omission: Chinese requires a measure word between number/demonstrative and noun (san ben shu = three MW books, not san shu).\n6. Applying English tense/aspect thinking - Chinese uses aspect markers le/guo/zhe and context.\n7. Not understanding the topic-prominent nature of Chinese sentences.\n\nGRAMMAR OVERVIEW:\nChinese grammar is ISOLATING: no conjugation, no declension, no gender, no articles. Grammar is expressed through word order, particles, and context. Key structures: topic-comment (zhege, wo bu xihuan = this, I not like), ba construction (ba + object + verb for disposal), bei construction (passive), complement of result (verb + result), complement of direction, complement of degree. Aspect particles: le (completed action/change of state), guo (experiential), zhe (ongoing state), zai (progressive action).\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nHSK (Hanyu Shuiping Kaoshi): THE standard Chinese proficiency test. 6 levels (HSK 1-6, new HSK has 9 levels). HSK 4 required for Chinese university undergraduate admission. HSK 5-6 for graduate programs. Tests reading, writing, and listening. HSKK (speaking test) separate. YCT (Youth Chinese Test) for younger learners.")

# Cantonese
expand_file("cantonese", "\n\nCOMPLETE TONAL SYSTEM:\nCantonese has SIX tones (some analyses count 9 by distinguishing checked/entering tones): Tone 1 (high level): si=poem. Tone 2 (high rising): si=history. Tone 3 (mid level): si=to try. Tone 4 (low falling): si=time. Tone 5 (low rising): si=market. Tone 6 (low level): si=yes. The three additional checked tones (7, 8, 9) are short versions of tones 1, 3, 6 ending in -p, -t, -k stops. This six-tone system is more complex than Mandarin's four tones and represents the biggest challenge for learners.\n\nCANTONESE VS MANDARIN:\nDespite sharing the Chinese character system, Cantonese and Mandarin are mutually UNINTELLIGIBLE in spoken form. Key differences: Cantonese has 6+ tones vs Mandarin 4. Cantonese preserves final consonants -p, -t, -k, -m that Mandarin lost. Cantonese has different grammatical particles. Cantonese uses different vocabulary for many basic concepts. Cantonese written vernacular uses characters not found in standard written Chinese. Understanding this distinction is essential - Cantonese is NOT just Mandarin with different pronunciation.\n\nROMANIZATION SYSTEMS:\nJyutping (the standard academic romanization): uses numbers 1-6 for tones. Yale romanization: older system using diacritics and h for tone marking, still found in many textbooks. Sidney Lau: used in some older Hong Kong materials. No single system dominates, but Jyutping is recommended for systematic learning.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not distinguishing all six tones - especially tones 3 (mid level) and 6 (low level).\n2. Not producing the final consonants -p, -t, -k (unreleased stops) and -m, -n, -ng.\n3. Applying Mandarin grammar rules to Cantonese (they differ significantly).\n4. Not understanding that Cantonese has its own grammatical particles: la, ga, wo, geh, lo, ah.\n5. Confusing Cantonese-specific vocabulary with Mandarin equivalents.\n6. Not mastering the aspect marker system specific to Cantonese: jo (completed), gan (progressive), gwo (experiential).\n\nGRAMMAR DIFFERENCES FROM MANDARIN:\nCantonese uses different sentence-final particles for mood/attitude (far more extensively than Mandarin). Word order for certain constructions differs: Cantonese bei (give) construction, Cantonese direct/indirect object ordering. Cantonese uses different aspect markers and complement structures.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nCantonese is the language of Hong Kong, Macau, Guangdong province, and the majority of overseas Chinese communities (historically, Chinese emigration was primarily from Guangdong). Cantonese opera tradition. Dim sum vocabulary (har gow, siu mai, cha siu bao). Hong Kong cinema and music (Cantopop). Understanding the cultural pride in Cantonese language maintenance.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nNo widely standardized Cantonese proficiency test equivalent to HSK. IELTS and university placement tests for Cantonese programmes in Hong Kong. Some Cantonese heritage language assessments available in diaspora communities.")

# Japanese
expand_file("japanese", "\n\nCOMPLETE WRITING SYSTEM:\nJapanese uses THREE scripts simultaneously: Hiragana (46 basic characters, used for native Japanese words, grammatical particles, and verb/adjective inflections), Katakana (46 characters, used for foreign loanwords, onomatopoeia, emphasis, and scientific terms), and Kanji (Chinese characters, approximately 2,136 joyo kanji for daily use). Each kanji typically has multiple readings: on-yomi (Sino-Japanese reading, from Chinese) and kun-yomi (native Japanese reading). The choice depends on context: compound words usually use on-yomi, standalone words usually use kun-yomi.\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nJapanese has a simple phonological system: 5 vowels (a /a/, i /i/, u /u/ (unrounded!), e /e/, o /o/) and limited consonant inventory. Key features: the u is UNROUNDED (unlike English oo), the r is a lateral flap (between English l and r), double consonants (gemination) are phonemic (kite = came, kitte = stamp), and vowel length is phonemic (obasan = aunt, obaasan = grandmother). Pitch accent exists but varies by dialect.\n\nPOLITENESS SYSTEM - KEIGO:\nJapanese has three levels of keigo (honorific language): Sonkeigo (respectful, elevating the subject's actions): irassharu instead of iru (to be), meshiagaru instead of taberu (to eat), ossharu instead of iu (to say). Kenjogo (humble, lowering your own actions): mairu instead of iku (to go), itadaku instead of morau (to receive), mousu instead of iu (to say). Teineigo (polite, -masu/-desu endings): the baseline polite form. Proper keigo usage is essential in Japanese business and social contexts.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Particle confusion: wa (topic) vs ga (subject) - the most fundamental and persistent grammar challenge. Wa marks the topic of the sentence (what we are talking about), ga marks the grammatical subject (who does the action) and introduces new information.\n2. Te-form conjugation errors - the te-form is essential for connecting clauses, making requests, progressive tense, and many other constructions. It follows complex but learnable patterns based on verb group and ending.\n3. Overuse of watashi (I) - Japanese frequently drops pronouns when context is clear.\n4. Not using appropriate politeness level for the social context.\n5. Applying English word order - Japanese is strictly SOV with particles marking grammatical roles.\n6. Kanji reading errors - choosing wrong reading (on-yomi vs kun-yomi).\n7. Counter/classifier confusion - Japanese has dozens of counters for different categories of objects.\n\nVERB SYSTEM:\nThree verb groups: Group 1 (u-verbs/godan): consonant-stem verbs with 5 possible ending changes. Group 2 (ru-verbs/ichidan): vowel-stem verbs dropping -ru and adding endings. Group 3 (irregular): only suru (to do) and kuru (to come). Conjugation forms: dictionary form, masu form (polite), te form (connecting), ta form (past), nai form (negative), ba/tara form (conditional), volitional, potential, passive, causative, causative-passive. The te-form patterns: Group 1 verbs change based on final consonant (ku->ite, gu->ide, su->shite, mu/bu/nu->nde, ru/tsu/u->tte).\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nUchi/soto (in-group/out-group) distinction affects all language choices. Aisatsu (greeting rituals) are extremely important. Business card exchange (meishi) vocabulary. Seasonal greetings. Japanese food vocabulary: sushi, ramen, tempura, izakaya. Anime/manga vocabulary as learning motivation. Understanding tatemae (public face) vs honne (true feelings).\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nJLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test): 5 levels, N5 (basic) through N1 (advanced). N2 required for most Japanese universities. N1 for graduate programs and professional positions. Tests reading, listening, vocabulary, and grammar (no writing or speaking). NAT-TEST and J-TEST as alternatives. BJT (Business Japanese Proficiency Test) for professionals.")

